shared_text:
Joshua Dillard
September 10 at 11:44 AM ·

Our schools here in Anderson have been getting some negative attention. There are amazing things happening here at all our schools, with our schools offering students so many more opportunities than other local schools, and most importantly a safe, positive learning environment. I challenge us to take a break from the negative posts and post 1 good thing you love about Anderson Community Schools. Let's end the week on a better note than how we started and unite our community under the great things we should focus on. If you're an alumni or current person in our schools (in any capacity)-help show Indiana why Anderson is the place to be! Let's light up facebook with all the great things here at ACS!

shared_text:
Plainfield Police Department
June 12 at 3:32 PM ·

On Wednesday, July 1, 2020, the new Indiana law involving holding cell phones while driving will take effect. This law prohibits the operator of a motor vehicle from holding or operating cell phones or other similar electronic devices while operating a motor vehicle.

The new law states that “a person may not hold or use a telecommunications device while operating a motor vehicle.” This law applies to wireless phones, personal digital assistants, pagers, or other text messaging devices.

Exceptions to this are if you are using hands-free or voice-operated technology like Bluetooth or if you are calling 911 to report an emergency.

Sending or reading a text message takes your eyes off the road for approximately 5 seconds and at a speed of 55 mph, that is like driving the length of an entire football field with your eyes closed!

As July 1st is approaching, now is a good time to begin thinking about how you plan on complying with this new law and purchase any needed equipment such as cell phone holders or hands-free technology before then.

Anderson Education Foundation is with Anderson Community Schools and Anderson High School at undefined.
June 11 at 5:39 PM ·

The Anderson Education Foundation is pleased to recognize the Top 20 academically ranked students of the Anderson High School graduating class of 2020.

They say "it takes a village" to raise a child. These students are examples of a "village" that includes not only each of their family members but also the greater ACS community of dedicated teachers, administrators, coaches and counselors. Each student was asked to select one educator who had a profound impact on their education and life. This was a challenging task as many noted in their comments. We hope you enjoy learning more about these talented students and the devoted teachers who helped them make the most of their school experience.

E2 Elementary
May 8 at 9:34 PM ·

The current “normal” for an E2 faculty meeting! We had social distancing and lots of fresh air. Dr. Scott created a special Teacher Appreciation Day for all of her staff members. Our E2 families drove through the parking lot and honked, waved, and even gave some teachers special gifts. It was uplifting for staff members to see and visit one another (with masks and at least 6’ apart), but especially to see some of our students today. Thank you to our E2 families, and to Dr. Scott, for this memorable Teacher Appreciation Day!

shared_text:
Joshua Dillard
April 23 at 12:17 PM ·

I support and appreciate all Anderson Community Schools are doing for our community. And I know that while our efforts might not be perfect, I wouldn't want to be a part of any other school community. I work personally with teachers, bus drivers, administration, substitutes, para professionals, lunch ladies, and many more staff to name, but are all missing the normal routines of school, but most of all we miss our students. So when I see people being nasty about the elearning packets or things like this it hurts because of all the selfless effort to help our community. Thank you ACS Family for making ACS the best!

So when I see people being nasty about the elearning packets or things like this it hurts because of all the selfless effort to help our community. Thank you ACS Family for making ACS the best!

OBITUARIES.HERALDBULLETIN.COM
Remembering the life of Joann Maddox 1956 - 2020

Anderson/District 26 Career Center
April 17 at 11:11 PM ·

It is with a sad heart that we share this news about one of our beloved educators, Joann Maddox. Mrs. Maddox was an admirable teacher, colleague, and leader that served as a source of light and joy to those she interacted with. She was full of laughter, smiles, good stories, and good advice. While at D26, Mrs. Maddox worked with students pursuing a CNA certification. She also served on the leadership committee and helped to make important decisions based on the expertise she had gained with over 40 years of experience in education. She was a wonderful person and had a tremendous amount of love for the students. Mrs. Maddox served D26 and Anderson Community Schools well and will be dearly missed.

https://obituaries.heraldbulletin.com/obituary/joann-maddox-1079032427/

The Herald Bulletin
April 16 at 5:00 PM ·

SENIORS, SUBMIT YOUR LETTER TODAY!
The Class of 2020 will finish its senior year at home, instead cruising the halls with friends, attending prom, starring in one final performance or playing in one last game. The Herald Bulletin would like to offer seniors a chance to put their thoughts about this unprecedented situation into words. Seniors can reflect on their high school careers, thank teachers, bid goodbye to friends and let everyone know about their future plans. It can't replace what these senior shave lost, but hopefully it can offer some closure. Seniors who would like to participate can send their 500-700 word letter and a photo to Heather Bremer at heather.bremer@heraldbulletin.com. Video submissions, in addition to the letter, are welcome as well.

shared_text:
The ALLEY Theatre
April 15 at 2:02 PM ·

THE ALLEY THEATRE is grieving the loss today of our friend and fellow actor/director/mentor/friend, BILL MALONE. His body relinquished itself to the complications of COVID-19, and his passing in the early morning hours of April 15th will be felt by those who shared life with him, onstage and off. His impact on THE ALLEY THEATRE, MAINSTAGE THEATRE, GEETING SUMMER THEATRE, THE COMMONS THEATRE, BALL STATE THEATRE, and the community at large, will be felt for years to come. His presence in and around all who worked with him will not leave as quickly has his body did.

Our love goes out to all his family and friends. We remember his smile, his voice, his love of theatre…and the gift he had to turn low comedy into high art.

ANDERSON'S MAINSTAGE THEATRE and THE ALLEY THEATRE are coordinating a "CELEBRATION OF BILL & HIS HEARTBEAT IN OUR THEATRE COMMUNITY" for a time when we can all be together...more information to follow.

shared_text:
Carrie Mote Craig is with Dale Craig.
April 10 at 3:53 PM ·

Love my students! They created this chat group with our school logo and have been inviting others in! They asked me to move with them to Highland next year! I have had them for 3 months before Corona set in...... miss them, but still trying to stay connected! Never doubt the difference you make with a child!

🤣😂One of my students’ mothers.....
“Carter had just showed me a couple days ago how he is on Facebook with you and made the comment that you and him were "homies" and "you always know how to reach your homies.”😂

“I just think it is so wonderful how everyone has come together. We might not have all the answers but at least we are all faking it till we make it together. I think it is important for Carter to have his own personal form of communication with you as well. There will be times I'm sure where his guess is as good as mine and will need extra help. Thank you!!”

ACS delivered 14,504 meals yesterday to 3,626 families. We are continuing to tweak the procedures, and will make multiple runs through neighborhoods where possible (only one meal-set per child - even non ACS kiddos). You can wave down any yellow bus you see and get food. Make sure you do wave so the driver knows you need food. AHS and HMS will also have meals on hand if you would rather drive there.

10-Noon every Monday and Wednesday thru the rest of the school year.
